    <title>Combined summary - Relax OP_RETURN standardness restrictions</title>
    <updated>2025-05-22T02:59:06.544941+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://gnusha.org/pi/bitcoindev/rhfyCHr4RfaEalbfGejVdolYCVWIyf84PT2062DQbs5-eU8BPYty5sGyvI3hKeRZQtVC7rn_ugjUWFnWCymz9e9Chbn7FjWJePllFhZRKYk=@protonmail.com/T/#u#mb13230a0c1c39b82b74f928791726d6a254063a4" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The discussion within the Bitcoin development community reflects a nuanced approach to managing and optimizing transaction practices, particularly concerning the use of OP_RETURN for embedding data in the blockchain. Historically, standardness rules, including restrictions on OP_RETURN outputs, have been implemented with several objectives: mitigating DoS attacks, preserving upgrade hooks, and discouraging undesirable practices like extensive data storage on the blockchain. These rules, especially the limit on the number and size of OP_RETURN outputs, were designed as a nudge to discourage blockchain bloat while still accommodating legitimate uses.

However, innovative workaround methods, such as Citrea's use of Taproot outputs for embedding data, demonstrate that these restrictions have not entirely prevented developers from storing data on-chain. Instead, they've led to alternative strategies that may circumvent the spirit of these limitations without necessarily adhering to their letter. This situation highlights a critical assessment of the current standardness rules' efficacy in curbing unwanted data storage practices. The proposal to eliminate restrictions on OP_RETURN outputs emerges against this backdrop, advocating for the removal of both the size limit of scriptPubKey for OP_RETURN outputs and the constraint on their quantity per transaction. This proposition aims to address the unintended encouragement of less desirable data storage methods by the existing rules.

The conversation underscores a broader debate on balancing technical constraints with the network's evolving needs and the creative solutions developers employ to meet those needs. By considering the removal of OP_RETURN restrictions, the community is engaging in a forward-looking dialogue on how best to adapt the blockchain's protocol to support new functionalities and protocols without compromising its integrity or functionality. This ongoing discussion reflects the dynamic nature of blockchain technology governance, where adjustments are continually evaluated in light of emerging challenges and innovations.</summary>
